The list of restricted countries is to be scrapped and any traveller with valid documents just needs to have a recent negative COVID-19 test before coming to enjoy SA. Sally Burdett spoke to Sisa Ntshona, CEO of SA Tourism. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The tourism sector has welcomed the easing of travel restrictions allowing visitors from any country to enter South Africa.
But the decision may be hamstrung as several key target markets are experiencing a second wave in coronavirus infections. READ: Making sense of international travel dos and don'ts As a result, many of those countries will prevent potential tourists from visiting South Africa. The tourism industry contributes 9 percent to the country’s GDP and employs about a million people.